Core Fundamentals & OOP

Four Pillars of OOP: Explain Abstraction, Encapsulation, Inheritance, and Polymorphism with real-world examples.

Interface vs. Abstract Class: An interface is a contract (usually for "can-do" behaviors), while an abstract class is for "is-a" relationships and can hold state.
== vs. equals(): == compares memory references; .equals() compares the actual content of objects.
Why are Strings Immutable? To ensure security, thread safety, and to optimize memory via the String Pool.

JDK vs. JRE vs. JVM: JDK is for development; JRE provides the environment to run apps; JVM executes the bytecode.
Automatic Unboxing: When an Integer object is compared to a primitive int with ==, the object is automatically converted to its primitive value.
The Reference Trap: Comparing two Integer objects with == checks if they are the same object in memory, not if they have the same value.
Integer Cache: By default, Java caches Integer objects for values from -128 to 127.

Modern Recommendation: Avoid using new Integer(int) as it has been deprecated. Use Integer.valueOf(int) or direct autoboxing (Integer i = 1000;) for better memory efficiency.
Inheritance ("Is-A" Relationship)
Inheritance allows a class to derive behavior and data from a parent class.
Mechanism: Using the extends keyword.
Best Use Case: When there is a clear, strict hierarchy (e.g., SavingAccount is a BankAccount).
Pros: Code reuse; provides a common interface for related types.
Cons: Tight Coupling. Changes in the parent class can break subclasses (the "Fragile Base Class" problem). It is fixed at compile-time and cannot be changed at runtime.
2. Composition ("Has-A" Relationship)
Composition involves building complex objects by combining simpler objects as pieces.
Mechanism: Including an instance of another class as a private field.
Best Use Case: When you want to reuse functionality without the baggage of a hierarchy (e.g., a Car has a Engine).
Pros: Loose Coupling. You can swap the internal object at runtime (Dependency Injection). It is more flexible and easier to test.
Design Rule: "Favor composition over inheritance." This is a core principle microservices and cloud-native design.
3. Polymorphism ("Many Forms")
Polymorphism is the ability of different objects to respond to the same method call in their own specific way.
Mechanism: Usually achieved via Interfaces or Method Overriding.
Best Use Case: When you want to write code that works with a general type, but behaves differently based on the specific object passed in (e.g., calling .processPayment() on both CreditCard and PayPal objects).
Pros: Allows for "Pluggable" code. You can add new types without changing the existing logic that uses them


In Java, the primary difference between a string literal and a string created with the new keyword (often called a String object) lies in how they are stored in memory and handled by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).
Key Differences
Feature
String Literal ("abc")
String Object (new String("abc"))
Storage Location
Stored in the String Constant Pool (a special part of the Heap).
Stored in the regular Heap memory area.
Creation
Created by enclosing text in double quotes: String s = "Hello";.
Created using the new keyword: String s = new String("Hello");.
Reuse
JVM reuses the same instance if the literal already exists in the pool (Interning).
Forces the creation of a new object every time, even if an identical string exists elsewhere.
Efficiency
More memory-efficient and faster due to caching.
Less efficient; consumes more memory by creating duplicate objects.

Comparison Behavior
The way you compare strings depends on how they were created:
Using == operator: Compares memory addresses (references).
"abc" == "abc" is true because they point to the same object in the pool.
new String("abc") == new String("abc") is false because they are different objects in heap memory.
Using .equals() method: Compares the actual character content.
str1.equals(str2) will be true for both literals and objects if their text is identical.
Best Practices
Prefer Literals: Always use string literals ("text") for standard text to take advantage of JVM optimization.
Use .intern(): If you have a String object and want to move it to the pool for reuse, you can use the intern() method.
Always use .equals(): For comparing the value of strings, never rely on == unless you specifically need to check if they are the exact same instance in memory.
.equals() Method (Content/Value Comparison)
The .equals() method is used to check if two objects have the same internal state or content.
Overriding: By default, the equals() method in the Object class behaves exactly like ==. However, many built-in classes like String, Integer, and Date override it to compare values.
Best Practices
Always use .equals() when comparing objects (especially Strings) unless you explicitly want to check if they are the same physical instance.
Handle null values: To avoid a NullPointerException, use Objects.equals(a, b) (available since Java 7) or place the literal first: "desiredValue".equals(userInput).
Primitives: Use == for int, boolean, char, etc.. For floating-point types (float, double), consider using a threshold or BigDecimal due to precision issues


Error(checked ) vs exception (runtime)
In Java, the primary difference between checked and unchecked exceptions is whether the compiler forces you to handle them.


Key Differences
Feature
Checked Exceptions
Unchecked Exceptions
Check Time
Verified at compile-time.
Verified at runtime.
Handling
Mandatory: Must be handled with try-catch or declared with throws.
Optional: Compiler does not require explicit handling.
Parent Class
Inherit from java.lang.Exception (excluding RuntimeException).
Inherit from java.lang.RuntimeException or java.lang.Error.
Typical Cause
External factors outside the program's control (e.g., missing file, network error).
Programming bugs or logic errors (e.g., null pointers, dividing by zero).

Examples
Checked: IOException, SQLException, FileNotFoundException, ClassNotFoundException.
Unchecked: NullPointerException, ArithmeticException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException, IllegalArgumentException.
Best Practices
Use Checked Exceptions for Recoverable Errors: If the calling code can reasonably be expected to recover (e.g., by prompting for a new filename if one is missing), use a checked exception.
Use Unchecked Exceptions for Programming Errors: If the error is due to faulty logic or invalid inputs that should have been validated, use an unchecked exception.
Avoid Overuse of Checked Exceptions: Modern Java development, particularly in frameworks like Spring, often favors unchecked exceptions to avoid cluttered method signatures and excessive try-catch blocks.
Custom Exceptions: When creating your own exception, extend Exception for checked and RuntimeException for unchecked behavior.
