Red-Black Tree is a type of self-balancing binary search tree (BST) that ensures the tree remains approximately balanced, guaranteeing logarithmic time complexity for core operations. In Java, this data structure is the underlying engine for several key parts of the standard library, including TreeMap and TreeSet.
1. Core Properties
To maintain balance, every node in a Red-Black Tree must follow five strict rules:
Color Property: Every node is either Red or Black.
Root Rule: The root node is always Black.
External Rule: All leaf nodes (NIL/null nodes) are considered Black.
Red Constraint: A Red node cannot have a Red child (no two Red nodes can be adjacent).
Uniform Black Depth: Every path from a node to any of its descendant leaf nodes must contain the same number of Black nodes.
2. Performance and Efficiency
Red-Black Trees provide a reliable worst-case time complexity of
O(logn)cap O open paren log n close paren
𝑂(log𝑛) for search, insertion, and deletion.
Vs. Standard BST: Unlike a normal BST, which can become skewed into a linked-list-like structure
O(n)cap O open paren n close paren
𝑂(𝑛)), Red-Black Trees automatically rebalance via rotations and recoloring.
Vs. AVL Trees: AVL trees are more strictly balanced, making them faster for lookups. However, Red-Black Trees are generally faster for frequent insertions and deletions because they require fewer rotations to maintain their "looser" balance.
Red-Black Trees are critical for high-performance data management in Java:
