Multithreading & Concurrency
Thread vs. Runnable: You can create a thread by extending the Thread class or implementing the Runnable interface (preferred for better code design).
Synchronized Method vs. Block: A synchronized method locks the entire object, while a block provides granular control by locking only a specific code section.
Deadlock: A situation where two threads are waiting for each other to release locks forever. Prevent this by acquiring locks in a consistent order.
Volatile Keyword: Ensures a variable's value is always read from and written to main memory, preventing thread-local caching issues.
In Java, a Condition (created via lock.newCondition()) provides the same functionality as Object.wait() and Object.notify(), but with more control. It allows you to have multiple waiting sets per lock, making it more efficient for complex coordination like the Producer-Consumer problem.
Try-Finally: Always wrap lock.unlock() in a finally block to prevent deadlocks if an exception occurs.
While-Loop: Always check the condition inside a while loop (not if) to protect against spurious wake-ups.
Virtual Threads: In Java 21+, ReentrantLock and Condition are highly optimized for Virtual Threads. Unlike synchronized blocks, they do not "pin" the virtual thread to the underlying OS thread, making your application significantly more scalable


ava's concurrency model has shifted toward Structured Concurrency and Virtual Threads, significantly simplifying high-scale multi-threading while maintaining the core principles of the Java Memory Model.
1. The volatile Keyword
volatile is a lightweight synchronization modifier that ensures Visibility and prevents Instruction Reordering.
Memory Visibility: It forces the thread to read and write variables directly from/to main memory instead of a CPU cache. This ensures that if Thread A updates a flag, Thread B sees it immediately.
No Atomicity: It does not make compound operations (like count++) atomic. For such operations, use AtomicInteger or synchronized blocks.
Instruction Reordering: It establishes a "happens-before" relationship, preventing the compiler from reordering code around the volatile variable, which is critical for patterns like Double-Checked Locking.
2. Thread Pools (Executor Framework)
Thread pools manage a collection of worker threads to reduce the overhead of creating and destroying threads for every task.
FixedThreadPool: Maintains a constant number of threads; best for stable, predictable workloads.
CachedThreadPool: Creates new threads as needed and reuses idle ones; ideal for many short-lived, asynchronous tasks.
ScheduledThreadPool: Used for executing tasks after a delay or periodically.
VirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor (Modern 2026 Standard): Introduced with Java 21, it uses Virtual Threads (lightweight, JVM-managed threads) that allow you to run millions of concurrent tasks with nearly zero overhead.
3. Java Concurrency API & Structured Concurrency
Java 26 refines the Structured Concurrency model, which simplifies parallel programming by treating related tasks in different threads as a single unit of work.
Task Lifetimes: It helps manage task hierarchies, ensuring that if a sub-task fails, all other related tasks are automatically canceled, preventing "thread leaks".
Virtual Threads: These are the backbone of modern Java concurrency. They map thousands of virtual threads to a single OS thread, making blocking I/O (like database calls) extremely efficient without needing complex reactive code.
4. Race Condition
A race condition occurs when two or more threads access shared data simultaneously and try to change it at the same time.
The final result depends on the unpredictable timing of the threads' execution.
Prevention: Use mutual exclusion through synchronized blocks, Lock objects, or atomic variables to ensure only one thread can modify the critical data at a time.
5. Round Robin Scheduling
In the context of multi-threading, Round Robin is a CPU scheduling algorithm where each thread is assigned a fixed time slot (quantum) in a circular order.
Fairness: It ensures that every thread gets an equal share of CPU time, preventing any single thread from monopolizing the processor.
Preemption: If a thread's time slot expires, it is paused and moved to the back of the queue so the next thread can run, giving the illusion of parallel execution on single-core systems


In Java, Thread Interruption is a cooperative mechanism that allows one thread to signal another thread to stop what it is currently doing. It is not a forceful "kill" switch; instead, it sets an internal boolean flag—the interrupt status—which the target thread must periodically check and act upon.
1. How Interruption Works
The Signal: Calling thread.interrupt() sets the thread's internal interrupt flag to true.
Blocking Methods: If a thread is blocked in a method like sleep(), wait(), or join(), it will immediately throw an InterruptedException and clear the interrupt flag (set it back to false).
Non-Blocking Code: If a thread is performing a long calculation (not blocked), it will not stop unless it manually checks its status using Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted().
2. Responding to InterruptedException
When you catch an InterruptedException, you have two primary responsibilities to ensure your code behaves well within a system:
Propagate the Exception: If possible, rethrow the exception so the caller knows the task was canceled.
Restore the Flag: If you cannot rethrow (e.g., inside a Runnable), you must call Thread.currentThread().interrupt() to set the flag back to true. This ensures higher-level frameworks (like thread pools) know the thread was interrupted.
3. Interruption in 2026 (Modern Java)
With the finalization of Virtual Threads (JDK 21+), interruption has become even more critical:
Non-Pinning: Unlike synchronized blocks, which can "pin" a virtual thread to an OS thread, modern locks like ReentrantLock are fully responsive to interruption without blocking carrier threads.
Responsive I/O: Modern Java I/O (NIO) is designed to be interruptible. If a thread is blocked on an InterruptibleChannel, an interrupt will close the channel and throw a ClosedByInterruptException.
Safe Cancellation: Use lock.lockInterruptibly() if you want a thread to be capable of stopping even while it is waiting to acquire a lock.
Summary of Key Methods
interrupt(): Sets the flag; wakes up the thread if it's blocked.
isInterrupted(): Checks the flag without changing it.
Thread.interrupted(): A static method that checks the flag and resets it to false. Use this only when you intend to act on the interruption immediately.


The Benefit
By using two different conditions (e.g., notFull and notEmpty), you can signal only the threads that can actually make progress. This avoids "spurious" wake-ups where a Producer accidentally wakes up another Producer instead of a Consumer.
In Java, ThreadLocal is a utility class that allows you to store data that is accessible only by a specific thread. It provides each thread with its own independent, isolated copy of a variable, ensuring that changes made by one thread do not affect any others.
Core Concept
Think of ThreadLocal as a "private locker" for each thread. Even if multiple threads use the same ThreadLocal instance, they are actually interacting with different values stored in their own internal memory.
Thread Isolation: Eliminates the need for complex synchronization (like synchronized or locks) because the data is never shared between threads.
Per-Thread Storage: Internally, each thread maintains a ThreadLocalMap where it stores these variables using the ThreadLocal instance as a key.
Common Use Cases
ThreadLocal is typically used for data that needs to be "global" within a thread’s execution but private to that thread.
User Sessions: Storing authenticated user IDs or security contexts during a single web request.
Database Connections: Ensuring each thread has its own dedicated connection during a transaction without constant parameter passing.
Non-Thread-Safe Objects: Wrapping objects like SimpleDateFormat so each thread has its own safe instance.
Logging Context: Carrying transaction IDs or request IDs through deep call stacks to enrich log messages.
Critical Pitfalls
Memory Leaks: In environments with thread pools (like modern web servers), threads are reused. If you don't call .remove(), the data from a previous request can persist and consume memory indefinitely.
Modern Alternatives: As of 2026, for modern Java development (Java 21+), Scoped Values are preferred over ThreadLocal for many scenarios because they are immutable, memory-efficient, and specifically designed for virtual threads
A ScopedValue acts as an implicit method parameter. Instead of passing a piece of data (like a User ID) through every method in a call chain, you "bind" it at the top of a scope.
Declaration: Define a static final ScopedValue.
Binding: Use ScopedValue.where(KEY, value) to create a "carrier".
Execution: Run a task within that scope using .run() or .call().
Automatic Cleanup: Once the run/call block finishes, the value is automatically discarded.
Virtual Thread Era: Because virtual threads are cheap and plentiful, standard ThreadLocal maps can become a significant memory burden. Scoped Values are optimized to be extremely lightweight, making them essential for modern scalable applications.
Security & Debugging: Because they are immutable, you can trust that a value set at the start of a request (like a tenantId) won't be modified by a bug in a downstream library


