Microservices 👍
In microservices, the Saga pattern enforces data consistency by replacing a single "all-or-nothing" distributed transaction with a coordinated sequence of local transactions. Because each microservice manages its own private database, traditional locking (ACID) is not possible at scale; Sagas instead achieve eventual consistency through two primary mechanisms:
1. Compensating Transactions (Rollback Logic)
For every local transaction that changes a service's state, a corresponding compensating transaction must be defined.
Forward Flow: Each service performs its work (e.g., reserving inventory) and triggers the next step via events.
Backward Recovery: if any step fails (e.g., payment declined), the Saga triggers the compensating actions of all previously successful steps in reverse order to "undo" their effects (e.g., un-reserving the inventory).
Property: These actions must be idempotent and retryable to ensure consistency even if the recovery process itself faces network issues.
2. Coordination Strategies
Sagas use one of two architectural styles to manage these sequences:
Choreography: Services communicate directly via asynchronous events without a central manager. Each service listens for specific events and reacts by running its own local transaction.
Orchestration: A central Orchestrator (Saga Execution Controller) coordinates the workflow. It tells each participant which transaction to execute and handles all failure/compensation logic from a central point, providing better visibility for complex business flows.
3. Counteracting Lack of Isolation
Because Sagas lack the "Isolation" of ACID transactions (other users might see intermediate data), they use semantic locks.
Intermediate States: A record is marked with a "PENDING" flag (e.g., APPROVAL_PENDING).
Application Logic: Other transactions are programmed to ignore or handle these pending records specially until the Saga officially completes or is fully compensated.
By 2026, Sagas are the standard for high-performance, cloud-native systems where availability and scalability are prioritized over the immediate consistency offered by older protocols like Two-Phase Commit (2PC)


KAFKA:
implementing Apache Kafka in Spring Boot has been streamlined through auto-configuration and native support for modern Java features like virtual threads.
1. Dependencies
Add the spring-kafka starter to your pom.xml. Spring Boot manages compatible versions automatically.
xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.kafka</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-kafka</artifactId>
</dependency>


Use code with caution.
2. Configuration
Define your Kafka broker and consumer/producer properties in application.yml or application.properties.
yaml
spring:
  kafka:
    bootstrap-servers: localhost:9092
    consumer:
      group-id: my-group
      auto-offset-reset: earliest
      key-deserializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer
      value-deserializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer
    producer:
      key-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
      value-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
  # Optional: Enable Virtual Threads for high-scale processing (Spring Boot 3.2+)
  threads:
    virtual:
      enabled: true


Use code with caution.
3. Producer Implementation
Spring Boot auto-configures a KafkaTemplate, which you can inject into any service to send messages.
java
@Service
public class KafkaProducerService {
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;


    public KafkaProducerService(KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate) {
        this.kafkaTemplate = kafkaTemplate;
    }


    public void sendMessage(String topic, String message) {
        kafkaTemplate.send(topic, message);
    }
}


Use code with caution.
4. Consumer Implementation
Use the @KafkaListener annotation to listen for messages on specific topics.
java
@Service
public class KafkaConsumerService {
    @KafkaListener(topics = "my-topic", groupId = "my-group")
    public void listen(String message) {
        System.out.println("Received message: " + message);
    }
}


Use code with caution.
5. 2026 Best Practices
Virtual Threads: If your application is I/O heavy, enable spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true. This allows Kafka listeners to process messages efficiently on lightweight virtual threads rather than expensive platform threads.
Topic Management: Use NewTopic beans to automatically create or modify topics on application startup.
Error Handling: Implement Dead Letter Topics (DLT) using @RetryableTopic to handle failed messages without blocking your main consumer stream.
Monitoring: Track Consumer Lag using built-in Spring Boot Actuator metrics to scale your consumer groups effectively.





